\v 9 \w Which|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w easier|strong="G2123"\w*:\f + \fr 2:9 \ft I suppose the point to be that the first is easier to \bd say\bd*, because no one can see whether it happened or not. But if you tell a paralytic to get up and he doesn't, you get egg on the face. The Lord did it that way to help them believe that He could really forgive sin. There was nothing wrong with the scribes' inference; indeed only God can forgive sin, so in fact Jesus was claiming to be God!\f* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w paralytic|strong="G3885"\w*, ‘\w Your|strong="G2532"\w* sins \w have|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* forgiven’, \w or|strong="G2228"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*, ‘\w Get|strong="G1453"\w* \w up|strong="G1453"\w*, pick \w up|strong="G1453"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w pallet|strong="G2895"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* start \w walking|strong="G4043"\w*!’?
