\s1 Blind Bartimaeus
\p 
\v 46 \w They|strong="G2532"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Jericho|strong="G2410"\w*. \w Then|strong="G2532"\w* \w as|strong="G1519"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w going|strong="G1607"\w* \w out|strong="G1607"\w* \w from|strong="G3844"\w* \w Jericho|strong="G2410"\w*,\f + \fr 10:46 \ft The parallel account in Luke has Jesus entering Jericho, not leaving it. At that time, there were two Jerichos, about a kilometer apart. What better place for an enterprising beggar than between the two towns? For a detailed discussion of the three accounts (also Matthew), please see the Appendix: Entering, or leaving Jericho?\f* \w with|strong="G3844"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w disciples|strong="G3101"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w large|strong="G2425"\w* \w crowd|strong="G3793"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w blind|strong="G5185"\w* Bartimaeus\f + \fr 10:46 \ft Mark is the only account that gives the man's name—evidently he was known (or at least became known).\f* (\w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Timaeus|strong="G5090"\w*) \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w sitting|strong="G2521"\w* \w by|strong="G3844"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* roadside \w begging|strong="G4319"\w*.
